===Verb===
{{en-verb|laughs|laughing|[[laughed]], [[laught]] (''obsolete'')}}

# {{intransitive}} To show [[mirth]], [[satisfaction]], or [[derision]], by [[peculiar]] [[movement]] of the [[muscle]]s of the [[face]], particularly of the [[mouth]], causing a [[lighting]] up of the face and [[eye]]s, and usually accompanied by the [[emission]] of [[explosive]] or [[chuckling]] [[sound]]s from the [[chest]] and [[throat]]; to [[indulge]] in [[laughter]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''Troilus and Cressida'', act I, scene ii:
#*: Queen Hecuba '''laughed''' that her eyes ran o’er.
#* {{rfdate}} Heywood’s Prov.:
#*: He '''laugheth''' that winneth.
# {{context|intransitive|figurative}} To be or appear cheerful, pleasant, mirthful, lively, or brilliant; to sparkle; to sport.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:John Dryden|John Dryden]]:
#*: Then '''laughs''' the childish year, with flowerets crowned.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]:
#*: In Folly’s cup still '''laughs''' the bubble Joy.
# {{intransitive}} To [[laugh at]], to make an object of [[laughter]] or [[ridicule]]; to make fun of; to [[deride]].
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Alexander Pope|Alexander Pope]]:
#*: No wit to flatter left of all his store, No fool to '''laugh''' at, which he valued more.
# {{transitive}} To [[affect]] or [[influence]] by means of laughter or ridicule.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''The Tempest'', act II, scene i:
#*: Will you '''laugh''' me asleep, for I am very heavy?
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''The Tempest'', act II, scene ii:
#*: I shall '''laugh''' myself to death.
# {{transitive}} To express by, or utter with, laughter; — with ''out''.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''Troilus and Cressida'', act I, scene iii:
#*: From his deep chest '''laughs''' out a loud applause.

